I think a lot about the fact that Millennials were the last generation able to build relationships with artists without being expected to critically evaluate them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then it wasn't so easy to determine that.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong nostalgia.
When "The Office" was on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was completely different from today's streaming era, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like, adding "spoiler warnings" to social media posts or discussing them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we long for that universal community that used to rule everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," which had so many one-liners that would now be memes.
We all used to say those lines, assuming that most people already understood them.
Today, you can't even assume that everyone knows something, even if it goes viral massively.
There is just too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Are we ever going to get out of this overload?
We are trapped in a cycle, constantly discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold on to our nostalgia while also accepting that the people who created the works we liked may have made big mistakes.
We are entering parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We know that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes along the way.
Since our collective consciousness regarding media has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who lift someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a phase of upheaval, and I am eager to see what the end result will be.
